<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1947-08-22T19:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1947-08-22T19:00:00-05:00" n="42" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d42">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">841.50/8–2247: Telegram</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                        State</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Embassy in the United
                                        Kingdom</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#left">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                                </seg>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1947-08-22T20:00:00-04:00">August
                                        22, 1947—8 p. m.</date>
                                </dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>3648. For Douglas. <gloss target="#t_NAC1">NAC</gloss> meeting this
                                afternoon confined to presentation by Eady of problem presented to
                                UK by Section 9 in view of increased <pb facs="0087" n="69" xml:id="pg_69"/> dollar shortage and potential increased
                                availability of goods in areas in which other payment possibilities
                                might be available to UK. He went on to say that discussions at the
                                technical level had indicated UK may have been interpreting Section
                                9 too strictly but that a solution of the UK problem would probably
                                require some form of agreed modification of Section 9. No decision
                                taken by <gloss target="#t_NAC1">NAC</gloss> other than work at the
                                technical level should continue. Eady returning London tomorrow.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Lovett</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>